---
import DocsLayout from "@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import DocsImage from "@/components/DocsImage.astro";

const nav = [
  {
    title: "Basics",
    items: [
      { text: "Overview", href: "#overview" },
      { text: "Interface map", href: "#interface" },
      { text: "Workflow", href: "#workflow" },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: "Steps",
    items: [
      { text: "1. Load old map", href: "#step-old-map" },
      { text: "2. Set reference map", href: "#step-new-map" },
      { text: "3. Prepare view", href: "#step-prepare" },
      { text: "4. Add control points", href: "#step-points" },
      { text: "5. Link and name", href: "#step-link" },
      { text: "6. Suggested links", href: "#step-suggest" },
      { text: "7. Clean up", href: "#step-cleanup" },
      { text: "8. Choose model", href: "#step-transform" },
      { text: "9. Compute", href: "#step-compute" },
      { text: "10. Visualize", href: "#step-visuals" },
      { text: "11. Compare", href: "#step-compare" },
      { text: "12. Export", href: "#step-export" },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: "Help",
    items: [{ text: "Tips", href: "#tips" }],
  },
];

const footerLinks = [
  { text: "Overview", href: "/docs" },
  { text: "Manual", href: "/docs/manual" },
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Tutorial"
  description="Step by step tutorial for MapAnalyst 2.0"
  sidebarTitle="Tutorial"
  nav={nav}
  footerLinks={footerLinks}
>
  <div class="content">
    <h1 id="overview">Tutorial for MapAnalyst 2.0</h1>
    <p>
      This tutorial explains the full workflow for comparing a historical map
      with a modern reference map. You will upload maps, place and link control
      points, compute transformations, and inspect distortion visualizations.
    </p>

    <h2 id="interface" class="mt-10">Interface map</h2>
    <p>
      The interface has three layers: the top menu bar, the map tools toolbar,
      and the analysis panels below. The left map is the historical image, the
      right map is the modern reference.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Top menu bar in red: file, edit, analyze, and help actions.</li>
      <li>
        Map tools in yellow: create and edit control points, measure, and draw.
      </li>
      <li>
        Settings panel in green: distortion grid, displacements, isolines.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial_annotated_layout.png"
      hint="tutorial_annotated_layout.png"
      caption="Annotated layout with callouts. "
      height="11rem"
    />

    <h2 id="workflow" class="mt-10">Workflow at a glance</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Upload the historical map.</li>
      <li>Choose a reference map (OSM or uploaded image).</li>
      <li>
        Place control points on both maps or let points get suggested and accept
        them.
      </li>
      <li>Link matching points and name them.</li>
      <li>Compute the transformation.</li>
      <li>Inspect residuals and visualizations.</li>
      <li>Export or reuse the control points.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="step-old-map" class="mt-10">1. Load the old map</h2>
    <p>
      Use the menu bar to upload the historical map image (PNG or JPG). The old
      map uses pixel coordinates, so the map is displayed in an image coordinate
      system.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Menu path: File &gt; Upload Old Map.</li>
      <li>The map will fit to the image bounds automatically.</li>
      <li>Uploading a new image clears old points and links.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-map-upload.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-map-upload.jpg"
      caption="Old map upload dialog and result."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-new-map" class="mt-10">2. Set the reference map</h2>
    <p>
      By default, the right map is OpenStreetMap. You can keep it as a live map,
      or upload a modern image instead.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Default: OSM base map with latitude and longitude.</li>
      <li>Optional: File &gt; Upload New Map to use an image.</li>
      <li>When using OSM, zoom and pan to the correct region.</li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote>
      If you upload a new map image, the new map uses pixel coordinates like the
      old map.
    </blockquote>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-map-reference.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-map-reference.jpg"
      caption="OSM view and optional upload."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-prepare" class="mt-10">3. Prepare the view</h2>
    <p>
      Align the view so that you can see matching locations on both maps. The
      coordinate readouts at the top help you verify pointer positions and
      measurements.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Use mouse wheel and drag to zoom and pan.</li>
      <li>Click Show All to reset the map extents.</li>
      <li>The Measure tool reports distance and angle.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-align-map.png"
      hint="tutorial-align-map.png"
      caption="Coordinate readouts and measure output."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-points" class="mt-10">4. Add and link control points</h2>
    <p>
      Control points are the backbone of the analysis. Use the New Point tool to
      place markers and the "Link" button to link them.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Choose New Point (red) in the map tools toolbar.</li>
      <li>
        Click a location on the old map, then the matching place on the new map
        (blue).
      </li>
      <li>Click the link button after two points are selected (yellow).</li>
      <li>Repeat for every clearly identifiable point.</li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote>
      More points usually improve stability, but focus on clear landmarks.
    </blockquote>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-link-points.png"
      hint="tutorial-link-points.png"
      caption="Placing points on both maps and linking them."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-link" class="mt-10">
      5. Import/export links or points and name points
    </h2>
    <p>
      You can rename the links by simply opening the link list and clicking
      "Rename". You can "save" your work by exporting and importing your linked
      points.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Click File &gt; Import &gt; Linked Points.</li>
      <li>Or click File &gt; Export &gt; Linked Points.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-points-list.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-points-list.jpg"
      caption="Selected points panel with Link and Rename."
      height="10rem"
    />
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-import-points.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-import-points.jpg"
      caption="Import and export in the top menu bar"
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-suggest" class="mt-10">6. Suggested links</h2>
    <p>
      MapAnalyst 2.0 can suggest linked control points using computer vision.
      Use suggestions to speed up the workflow, then review them before
      accepting.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        It is recommended to set a few points and to draw a polygon around the
        areas in both maps before suggesting links (for a better performance).
      </li>
      <li>Click Suggest Links in the map tools toolbar.</li>
      <li>Set minimum distance, max count, and color, then run.</li>
      <li>Accept or dismiss suggestions in the list or on the map.</li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote>
      Suggestions require the backend services to run. If you see an error,
      verify that the backend and optional CV dependencies are installed.
    </blockquote>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-polygon-rec.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-polygon-rec.jpg"
      caption="Drawing a polygon after setting a few points for a better performance."
      height="10rem"
    />
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-rec.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-rec.jpg"
      caption="Suggestion config dialog."
      height="10rem"
    />
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-rec-window.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-rec-window.jpg"
      caption="Suggestion window."
      height="10rem"
    />
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-rec-map.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-rec-map.jpg"
      caption="Suggestion interactions directly on the map."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-cleanup" class="mt-10">7. Clean up and adjust</h2>
    <p>
      Refine the control points before computation. Use selection tools to move,
      delete, or remeasure points.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Select Rect to select multiple points.</li>
      <li>Move Point to drag selected points.</li>
      <li>Delete to remove points or links.</li>
      <li>Undo and Redo are available in the Edit menu.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-adjust-points.png"
      hint="tutorial-adjust-points.png"
      caption="Selection rectangle, delete and moved points."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-transform" class="mt-10">8. Choose the model</h2>
    <p>
      Open the Analyze menu to choose which map to transform and which
      mathematical model to use.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Target Map sets the map that will be transformed.</li>
      <li>Choose Helmert (4), Affine (5), Affine (6), or Robust Helmert.</li>
      <li>Robust estimators have additional parameter dialogs.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-transform-menu.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-transform-menu.jpg"
      caption="Analyze menu with transformation selection."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-compute" class="mt-10">9. Compute results</h2>
    <p>
      Press Compute to run the analysis. The report lists model parameters and
      residual errors for each link.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Compute is available in the Analyze menu and map tools toolbar.</li>
      <li>The report shows parameters, RMSE, and residuals.</li>
      <li>Large residuals can indicate outliers.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-report.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-report.jpg"
      caption="Computation report modal."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-visuals" class="mt-10">10. Visualize distortions</h2>
    <p>
      Use the settings panel to enable the three primary visualizations:
      distortion grid, displacements, and isolines.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Distortion grid reveals local warping across the map.</li>
      <li>Displacements show residual vectors or circles at points.</li>
      <li>Isolines map local scale and rotation changes.</li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote>
      Distortion grids and isolines require at least three linked points.
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      It was very important to note that the settings of the visualizations
      matter. Try adjusting the settings like "Mesh Size" or "Interval" for
      better results.
    </blockquote>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-dist-grid.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-dist-grid.jpg"
      caption="Distortion grid on the map."
      height="12rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-compare" class="mt-10">11. Compare models</h2>
    <p>
      The comparison tool runs several transformations and summarizes their
      results. Use it to justify the model you choose.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Open Analyze &gt; Compare Transformations.</li>
      <li>Review the summary for scale, rotation, and deviations.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-comparison.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-comparison.jpg"
      caption="Comparison modal output."
      height="10rem"
    />

    <h2 id="step-export" class="mt-10">12. Export and reuse points</h2>
    <p>
      Use import and export to reuse control points or archive your work. The
      files are plain text and easy to inspect.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Export: old points, new points, or linked points.</li>
      <li>Import: same formats to restore a session.</li>
      <li>Comments starting with # are ignored.</li>
    </ul>
    <DocsImage
      name="tutorial-export.jpg"
      hint="tutorial-export.jpg"
      caption="Sample text file."
      height="6rem"
    />

    <h2 id="tips" class="mt-10">Tips and troubleshooting</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Use at least 2 links for Helmert and 3 for affine models.</li>
      <li>If the grid or isolines do not appear, recompute first.</li>
      <li>For OSM suggestions, zoom in so the area is not too large.</li>
      <li>When using custom polygons, finish with a double click.</li>
      <li>Link names help track landmarks in the residual report.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
